title: AI-Generated Code Security Checklist
content:
# AI-Generated Code Security Checklist

### (Codex · Cursor · Claude · Gemini)

## 0. Fundamental Rule (Non-Negotiable)

**All AI-generated code is untrusted by default.**
Any access to data, secrets, permissions, pricing, or costly operations **must be enforced on the server side**.

---

## 1. Architecture & Trust Boundaries

### ❌ Forbidden

* Frontend talking directly to the database
* API keys, secrets, or tokens in client-side code
* Sensitive calculations (prices, quotas, permissions) on the client

### ✅ Required

* Always use a **backend / middleware / API**
* Backend is the **single source of truth**
* Client is limited to:

  * rendering UI
  * collecting user intent
  * sending requests

**AI Rule**

> If code touches a database, payments, permissions, or secrets, it MUST be server-side.

---

## 2. Authentication ≠ Authorization

### ❌ Common AI mistake

```ts
if (user.isLoggedIn) {
  allowAction()
}
```

### ✅ Correct pattern

Every action or endpoint must explicitly verify:

* **who** the user is
* **what** they are allowed to do
* **which resources** they can access
* **under which conditions**

**AI Rule**

> Every endpoint must verify permissions, even for authenticated users.

---

## 3. “Don’t hide — withhold” (Premium & Protected Features)

### ❌ Anti-pattern

* Backend returns `isPremium: false`
* Frontend hides a button

### ✅ Secure pattern

* Backend never sends premium data unless authorized
* Backend rejects unauthorized requests outright

**AI Rule**

> Never trust the frontend to enforce business rules.

---

## 4. Secrets & Configuration

### ❌ Absolute prohibitions

* API keys in:

  * frontend JS/TS
  * mobile apps
  * HTML
  * client bundles
* Assuming `.env` alone is safe

### ✅ Required

* Secrets stored only on:

  * backend
  * serverless functions
  * secure secret managers
* Environment variables must never be exposed to the client

**AI Rule**

> If the user can see it, it is already compromised.

---

## 5. Sensitive Logic & Business Rules

### ❌ Forbidden

* Price calculations on the client
* Quotas or limits on the client
* Scoring or ranking on the client
* Permission logic on the client

### ✅ Required

* All sensitive logic runs on the server
* Client receives final results only

**AI Rule**

> The client never decides “how much”, “how many”, or “who can”.

---

## 6. Input Handling & Injection Safety

### ❌ Typical risks

* SQL injection
* Prompt injection
* Code injection
* CSV / Excel injection
* XSS

### ✅ Mandatory protections

* Sanitize **all** user input
* Validate types and formats
* Escape content before storage or execution
* Strictly separate:

  * data
  * instructions
  * prompts

**AI Rule**

> User input is data, never instructions.

---

## 7. Rate Limiting & Abuse Prevention

### ❌ Dangerous pattern

* Unlimited “send”, “generate”, or “export” actions

### ✅ Required

* Rate limiting per:

  * user
  * IP
  * action
* Protection against bots, spam, brute force

**AI Rule**

> Any action that costs time or money must be rate-limited.

---

## 8. Logging & Observability

### ❌ Never log

* passwords
* tokens
* API keys
* full email addresses
* sensitive personal data

### ✅ Best practices

* Internal logs only
* Mask or hash sensitive fields
* Separate user-visible logs from system logs

**AI Rule**

> Logs are permanent. Assume attackers will read them.

---

## 9. Error Handling (Fail Secure)

### ❌ Bad practice

* Exposing stack traces
* Revealing database details
* Verbose internal errors

### ✅ Secure approach

* Generic user-facing errors
* Detailed errors only in private logs

**AI Rule**

> Errors should inform developers, not attackers.

---

## 10. LLM-Specific Safety Rules

### ❌ Forbidden

* LLM-generated SQL executed directly
* LLM-generated code executed without sandboxing
* LLM deciding permissions or access rules
* Direct LLM access to DB, filesystem, or secrets

### ✅ Required

* Validation layers
* Sandboxed execution
* Allow-listed operations only
* LLM **suggests**, system **enforces**

**AI Rule**

> The LLM proposes. The system decides.

---

## 11. Dependency & Supply Chain Security

### ✅ Required

* Keep dependencies up to date
* Monitor critical CVEs
* Do not auto-add unknown packages suggested by the AI

**AI Rule**

> Old dependencies are known attack surfaces.

---

## 12. Cross-Model Security Auditing

### Recommended practice

* Generated with Codex → audited by Claude
* Generated with Claude → audited by Gemini
* Generated with Cursor → audited by another model

**AI Rule**

> A second model catches what the first one misses.

---

## 13. Mandatory Pre-Merge Security Gate

Before merging AI-generated code:

* [ ] No direct DB access from frontend
* [ ] No exposed secrets
* [ ] Authorization checked on every action
* [ ] Sensitive logic on server
* [ ] All inputs sanitized
* [ ] Rate limiting enabled
* [ ] Logs contain no sensitive data
* [ ] Errors are non-verbose
* [ ] Sandbox intact
* [ ] Cross-model audit completed

---

## System Prompt for Codex / Cursor / Claude

> **“All code you generate must comply with the AI-Generated Code Security Checklist.
> If a feature cannot be implemented securely, you must refuse and explain why.”**

---
